{{Infobox video game | title = Ashes of the Singularity | image = Ashes of the Singularity video game cover art 2017.jpg | caption = | developer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Oxide Games]]|[[Stardock Entertainment]]}} | publisher = Stardock Entertainment | director = | producer = | designer = | programmer = | artist = | writer = | composer = {{Plainlist| * [[Geoff Knorr]] * Michael Curran * Richard Gibbs}} | engine = | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]] | released = March 31, 2016 | genre = [[Real-time strategy]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] }}
'''''Ashes of the Singularity''''' is a [[real-time strategy]] [[video game]] developed by [[Oxide Games]] and [[Stardock Entertainment]]. The game was released for [[Microsoft Windows]] on March 31, 2016.
On November 10, 2016, '''''Ashes of the Singularity: Escalation''''' was released. It is a standalone expansion that adds to the base game with more units, maps, and structures, as well as several interface tweaks. The total player count was also increased from 8 to 16 players. The expansion was later merged into the base game on February 16, 2017, after it became apparent that the separate games divided the player community.<ref name="stardock-escalation-merge">{{cite web|last1=Wardell|first1=Brad|authorlink1=Brad Wardell|title=ONE COMMUNITY: Merging the Singularity|url=https://www.stardock.com/community/article/481856/ONE-COMMUNITY-Merging-the-Singularity|publisher=[[Stardock]]|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref>
==Gameplay== ''Ashes of the Singularity'' is a [[real-time strategy]] [[video game]].<ref name="pcgamer_early_access">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/ashes-of-the-singularity-hitting-early-access-next-week/|title=Ashes of the Singularity hitting Early Access next week|last=Sykes|first=Tom|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=October 15, 2015|accessdate=January 8, 2016}}</ref> Its main distinction is its ability to handle thousands of individual units engaging in combat simultaneously, far greater than most other games of its kind, across large maps and without abstraction. This is achieved through a newly developed engine called ''Nitrous'' designed to fully leverage modern [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[multi-core processor]]s, reflected in the relatively high system requirements (which include a quad-core processor). To allow players to effectively control such large numbers of units, groups of individual units can be combined into "meta-units" which operate in a cohesive manner, upon which complex strategies can be developed.<ref name="oxide-faq">{{cite web|author1=Oxide Games|title=''Ashes of the Singularity'' FAQ|url=http://www.ashesofthesingularity.com/game/faq|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref>
==Development== ''Ashes of the Singularity'' was the first video game released with [[DirectX 12]] support.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/10/23/stardock-launches-first-ever-directx-12-game/|title=Stardock launches first ever DirectX 12 game|last=Hillier|first=Brenna|work=[[VG247]]|date=October 23, 2015|accessdate=January 8, 2016}}</ref> It is also one of the first to support [[Vulkan (API)|Vulkan]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Takahashi |first1=Dean |url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/03/01/how-ashes-of-the-singularity-will-enable-massive-planetary-battles-with-huge-sci-fi-armies/ |title=How Ashes of the Singularity enables massive planetary battles with huge sci-fi armies |date=March 1, 2016 |website=[[GamesBeat]] |publisher=[[VentureBeat]] |accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> An in-development version of the game was released commercially via [[Steam Early Access]] on October 22, 2015.<ref name="pcgamer_early_access" /> The full version of the game was released on [[Windows]] on March 31, 2016.<ref name="pcgamer_release_trailer">{{cite web | url=http://www.pcgamer.com/ashes-of-the-singularity-release-date-revealed-in-new-trailer/ | title=Ashes of the Singularity release date revealed in new trailer | work=[[PC Gamer]] | publisher=[[Future plc]] | first=Andy | last=Chalk | date=March 9, 2016 | accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>
Because of the game's early DirectX 12 support and extensive use of [[Parallel computing|parallel computation]], it is commonly used as a [[benchmark (computing)|benchmark]]. Controversy erupted when Nvidia GPUs were found to perform poorly relative to their AMD counterparts on early beta versions of ''Ashes'';<ref name="pcworld-dx12">{{cite web|last1=Mah Ung|first1=Gordon|title=Windows 10's DirectX 12 graphics performance tested: More CPU cores, more oomph|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2971612/software-games/windows-10s-radical-directx-12-graphics-tech-tested-more-cpu-cores-more-performance.html|website=[[PCWorld]]|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref><ref name="pcworld-aots-beta-benchmark">{{cite web|last1=Dingman|first1=Hayden|title=''Ashes of the Singularity'' hits Steam, letting you benchmark DirectX 12 at home|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2996523/software-games/ashes-of-the-singularity-hits-steam-letting-you-benchmark-directx-12-at-home.html|website=[[PCWorld]]|accessdate=24 February 2017|date=22 October 2015}}</ref> this was due to the game's use of asynchronous compute and shading features which are implemented in hardware on AMD [[Graphics Core Next]] GPUs but had to be performed in software on Nvidia GPUs.<ref name="tomshardware-beta-benchmark">{{cite web|last1=Wallossek|first1=Igor|title=''Ashes Of The Singularity'' Beta: Async Compute, Multi-Adapter & Power|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/reviews/ashes-of-the-singularity-beta-async-compute-multi-adapter-power-consumption,4479.html|website=[[Tom's Hardware]]|accessdate=24 February 2017|date=29 February 2016}}</ref>
==Reception== {{Video game reviews | MC = 69/100<ref name="metacritic" /> }} ''Ashes of the Singularity'' received an "average" reception from critics according to aggregate review website [[Metacritic]].<ref name="metacritic">{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/ashes-of-the-singularity | title=Ashes of the Singularity for PC Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>
Giving it a good score of 7.7, IGN wrote: "This is a warzone where the shrewd general looking at the bigger picture will triumph over the fast-thinking ace with lightning hotkeys."<ref name=IGN>{{Citation | last =Hafer | first =TJ | date =March 31, 2016 | title =ASHES OF THE SINGULARITY REVIEW | publisher = | publication-place = | url =http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/03/31/ashes-of-the-singularity-review | accessdate =January 8, 2017 }}</ref>
[[PC Gamer]] gave it a score of 75/100.<ref name=PCgamer>{{Citation | last =Johnson | first =Leif | date =April 1, 2016 | title =ASHES OF THE SINGULARITY REVIEW | publisher =[[PCGamer]] | publication-place = | url =http://www.pcgamer.com/ashes-of-the-singularity-review/ | accessdate =January 8, 2017 }}</ref> [[GameSpot]] gave it a mixed review.<ref name=Gamespot>{{Citation | last =Starkey | first =Daniel | date =April 25, 2016 | title =Ashes of the Singularity Review | publisher =[[Gamespot]] | publication-place = | url =http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/ashes-of-the-singularity-review/1900-6416414/ | accessdate =January 8, 2017 }}</ref>
