The '''IAWTV Awards''' is an annual event hosted by the [[International Academy of Web Television]], currently based in [[Los Angeles]], that honors [[web series]] creators and talent in over a dozen categories, voted on by the IAWTV membership.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iawtv.org/about-the-iawtv-awards/|title=About the IAWTV Awards|website=International Academy of Web Television|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-16}}</ref>  

== History ==

The IAWTV Awards are hosted annually by the International Academy of Web Television (IAWTV), which was founded in 2008 and is devoted to the advancement of the arts and sciences of web television production.

=== Inception ===

In 2010, before the IAWTV Awards existed, the IAWTV hosted the [[2nd Streamy Awards|2nd annual]] [[Streamy Awards]].<ref name="Tilzy">{{cite news|url=http://www.tilzy.tv/transparency-the-streamys-and-the-iawtv.htm|title=Transparency. The Streamys and The IAWTV|author=Tilsner, Jamison|date=March 4, 2009|accessdate=2009-09-27|publisher=Tilzy.tv|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610073605/http://www.tilzy.tv/transparency-the-streamys-and-the-iawtv.htm|archivedate=June 10, 2009|df=}}</ref> The [[2nd Streamy Awards#Reception|poor reception]] of the event,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.endofshow.com/2010/04/12/2nd-streamy-awards-descend-into-farce/|title=2nd Streamy awards descend into farce|author=Kevin Beaumont|date=April 12, 2010|publisher=''End of Show''|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> and the surrounding controversy,<ref name="GigaOM2">{{cite web|url=http://gigaom.com/2010/04/12/the-streamy-awards-a-producers-apology-and-its-three-fails/|title=The Streamy Awards: A Producer’s Apology And Its Three Fails|author=Liz Shannon Miller|date=April 12, 2010|publisher=''GigaOM''|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> resulted in a two year hiatus for the Streamy Awards, and the subsequent creation of the IAWTV Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUS130977575220110807|title=Will the web series world support the new Streamy Awards?|last=|first=|date=|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref> The two awards ceremonies are both still running annually, though as completely separate entities.<ref name="Tvisual2">{{cite web|url=http://tvisual.org/2012/12/17/on-giving-the-streamys-and-the-iawtv-a-chance/|title=On Giving the Streamys (and the IAWTV) a Chance|author=Aymar Jean Christian|date=December 17, 2012|publisher=''Televisual''|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>

=== 2011–present ===

Since its inception in 2011, the IAWTV has held award ceremonies every year (with the exception of 2016), presenting awards to web series creators and talent in over a dozen categories, covering several genres. Notable IAWTV winners include [[Felicia Day]], [[Julia Stiles]] and [[Milo Ventimiglia]], as well as the critically acclaimed web series ''[[The Guild (web series)|The Guild]]'', ''[[Blue (web series)|Blue]]'', ''[[Anyone But Me]]'', ''[[Husbands (TV series)|Husbands]]'', ''[[Leap Year (TV_series)|Leap Year]]'', and ''[[Whatever, Linda]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://playbackonline.ca/2015/04/16/canadian-web-series-take-home-eight-iawtv-awards/|title=Canadian web series take home eight IAWTV Awards|access-date=2017-09-16}}</ref>

Between 2012 and 2015, the IAWTV Awards were held in [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=":02">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iawtv.org/about-the-iawtv-awards/|title=About the IAWTV Awards|website=International Academy of Web Television|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-16}}</ref> The 2017 ceremony took place in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=":02" />

