'''Space Integrated GPS/INS (SIGI)''' is a [[strapdown]] [[Inertial guidance system|Inertial Navigation Unit]] (INU) developed and built by [[Honeywell International]] to control and stabilize [[spacecraft]]s during flight.
SIGI has integrated [[global positioning]] and inertial [[navigation technology]] to provide three [[navigation]] solutions : ''Pure inertial, [[GPS]]-only and blended GPS/INS''.
==Current and Future Usage== SIGI have been employed on the [[International Space Station]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Lessons Leamed from Two Years of On-Orbit Global Positioning System Experience on International Space Station | work= PDF | publisher= NASA Johnson Space Center | url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20060020237_2006014558.pdf | accessdate=2006-09-27}}</ref> the Japanese [[H-II Transfer Vehicle]] (HTV)<ref>{{cite web|title=H-IIA Transfer Vehicle |work=Web Site |publisher=Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA) |url=http://www.jaxa.jp/missions/projects/rockets/htv/backnumber_e.html |accessdate=2006-10-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928072902/http://www.jaxa.jp/missions/projects/rockets/htv/backnumber_e.html |archivedate=September 28, 2006 }}</ref> the [[Boeing X-37]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Independent Assessment of X-37 Safety & Mission Assurance Processes and Design Features | work=PDF | publisher=NASA Headquarters Office of Safety & Mission Assurance | url=http://pbma.nasa.gov/docs/public/pbma/casestudies/X37_Independent_Assessment_Report.pdf | accessdate=2006-09-27 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002194217/http://pbma.nasa.gov/docs/public/pbma/casestudies/X37_Independent_Assessment_Report.pdf | archivedate=2006-10-02 | df= }}</ref> and [[X-40]].
SIGI is also proposed as the primary navigation system for [[Orion (Constellation program)|Orion]], which is scheduled to replace the [[Space Shuttle]].{{update after|2011|1|1}}
